The series of classical jurists closes with Herennius hlo- destinus, a pupil of Ulpian, and teacher of the young Maximinus about nn. 238, from whose writings the Digest contains three hundred and forty·five extracta.

After this tedious enumeration of the names of the most celebrated jurists‚ we may turn aslde to consider briefly the nature of their influence and the modes in which it was exercised, including their styles of teaching and of legal treatment. The establishment of the empire brought with it a considerable change in respect of the responsa prudentium· Under the free Republic it had been competent to any one 10 profess the law, and to give advice on consultation3 the form and effect of the responsa had been under no limitations. The influence of the jurists was one which the emperors would naturally find it difficult to destroy, not only because by its long and steady growth it had achieved a stature and a traditional position which might have long defied the direct attacks of opponente, but because it had always been independent of political rank, and un· connected with any constitutional office through which it might have been assailed.
